WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.100 --> 00:00:03.150
The energy transition needs a lot more critical minerals.

2
00:00:03.100 --> 00:00:05.812
Our water needs a lot fewer forever chemicals.

3
00:00:05.812 --> 00:00:07.875
Totally different crises, right?

4
00:00:07.875 --> 00:00:14.141
At the atomic level, they are weirdly the same problem: getting a material to grab, release, or break exactly the right thing.

5
00:00:14.141 --> 00:00:17.933
Clean-energy mineral demand could grow four to six times by 2040.

6
00:00:17.933 --> 00:00:20.708
Mining alone cannot get us there cleanly or quickly.

7
00:00:20.708 --> 00:00:24.791
So recycling, urban mining, and direct lithium extraction have to work.

8
00:00:24.791 --> 00:00:30.716
But that requires sorbents and extractants precise enough to separate nearly identical ions in messy real-world streams.

9
00:00:30.716 --> 00:00:32.833
PFAS flips the challenge around.

10
00:00:32.833 --> 00:00:38.441
First, capture PFOA and PFOS down to the EPA limit: four nanograms per liter each.

11
00:00:38.441 --> 00:00:40.266
Then actually destroy them.

12
00:00:40.266 --> 00:00:45.841
That second step is brutal because the carbon–fluorine bond packs about four hundred eighty-five kilojoules per mole.

13
00:00:45.841 --> 00:00:49.216
Today’s filters mostly move the problem into contaminated media.

14
00:00:49.216 --> 00:00:55.625
We could screen millions of recovery materials and catalysts, except the fast models tend to soften the exact physics that matters.

15
00:00:55.625 --> 00:01:04.025
At pores, vacancies, surfaces, and transition states, raw universal machine-learning potentials can misrepresent the energy landscape by fifteen to sixty percent.

16
00:01:04.025 --> 00:01:07.050
Great-looking candidates become expensive false positives.

17
00:01:07.050 --> 00:01:12.550
Lupine measures that error against local atomic coordination, then corrects energies and forces at runtime.

18
00:01:12.550 --> 00:01:23.575
Now the same fast screen can rank lithium-selective pores, cobalt-versus-nickel extractants, PFAS sorbents, and defluorination catalysts without pretending every atomic neighborhood behaves like a perfect bulk crystal.

19
00:01:23.575 --> 00:01:29.083
On the mineral side, corrected binding and migration energies guide separation and direct battery recycling.

20
00:01:29.083 --> 00:01:34.458
On the PFAS side, corrected barriers expose catalysts that will fail or poison themselves with fluoride.

21
00:01:34.458 --> 00:01:40.600
Machine-checked boundaries also flag predictions the data cannot support, before anybody builds a costly experiment around them.

22
00:01:40.600 --> 00:01:43.683
One campaign puts scarce atoms back into circulation.

23
00:01:43.683 --> 00:01:45.716
The other takes harmful ones out.

24
00:01:45.716 --> 00:01:49.175
Both move faster when we correct the same hidden error in the models.

25
00:01:49.175 --> 00:01:50.641
Recover what we need.

26
00:01:50.641 --> 00:01:52.191
Destroy what we don’t.

27
00:01:52.191 --> 00:01:54.441
Read the full case at Lupine Science.
